QA Summary

MLRA 17 - Arbuckle horizon standardization in 2-CHI SSA updated in SDJR

report version 0.2
2018-05-22


This report requires setting up a selected set in your local NASIS database:

  • load project by name
  • add data associated with MLRA map units into mapunit table
  • add data associated with old and new DMU into data mapunit table

MLRA Map Unit Text Notes

2w8cy: Arbuckle gravelly loam, 0 to 8 percent slopes, MLRA 17

This was originally a SDJR project mapunit that updated 021AoB. 021AoB (MLRA 17/15, LRU 7b, 6f) was not combined with 679AlC (MLRA 19/20, LRU 85k, 85m) due to different precip and maat. 679AlC is drier and warmer than 021AoB.

While working on the Arbuckle horizon standardization project in April 2018, I started updating 645AvB, Arbuckle gravelly loam, 3 to 8 percent slopes. I noticed that 645AvB and 021AoB (2w8cy) could be combined. 645AvB was not included in the gravelly loam, 2 to 8 percent slopes project because of the minor slope phase difference.

I will now combine 021A0B and 645AvB, and adjust textures and slopes to reflect both mu and dmu.

CA021: AoB; hd5w; Glenn County, California - Arbuckle gravelly loam, 2 to 8 percent slopes

CA645: AvB; hgcw; Tehama County, California - Arbuckle gravelly loam, 3 to 8 percent slopes

The component horizon is from the CA021 Arbuckle TUD which is in 021AoA.

Component ranges are from MUSum report and slopes were 0-3-19 % in report results Q10-Q50-Q90 for 021AoB. Some of the high slopes are due to line shift and the inclusion of steep adjacent risers as well as from the original mapping that included risers in the delineations due to scale. I am going with slopes of 0-3-8 % to stick more closely with the original concept.

MUSum slope results are 0-2-10% for 645AvB. There is line shift up onto slopes in 645AvB also.

I will make slopes 0-2-8% for this new mu.

This map unit occurs at 144 to 1405 feet elevation with 23 to 31 inches of precip determined by Q5 and Q95 from MUSum report.

The 021AoB MUD mentions that in the MLRA 15 portion of this map unit, this soil is on small, very gently sloping alluvial fans and benches, and smaller areas in the MLRA 17 portion are on low mounds and long, narrow ridges.

There is no mention of minor comps in either MUD. The CA021 TUD states In the Sacramento Valley the Arbuckle soils are near the Artois, Hillgate, Kimball and Tehama soils. In the foothills Arbuckle soils are on low benches along intermittent streams that drain areas of Corning and Newville soils. I will attempt to integrate the geomorphology and minor comps in regard to the proportional distribution in the 2 settings. 021AoB is about 50/50 between MLRA 15 and 17.

The legacy data in the NASIS dmu 021AoB has 8% unnamed (?), 5 % gullied land (the MUD mentions gullies 4 to 6 feet deep are in a few areas)and 2 % unnamed in depressions.

2y0f7: Arbuckle cobbly loam, 0 to 3 percent slopes, MLRA 17

This is a map unit that updates 021AoxA. This tabular edit project updates mu and dmu of series in SSA that were updated in sdjr to standardize and update all the major components and component horizons of the series within the SSA. 021AoB was updated in sdjr as new mu 2w8cy that used the CA021 TUD in 021AoA for component horizon.

CA021: AoxA; hd5x; Glenn County, California - Arbuckle cobbly loam, 0 to 3 percent slopes

The component horizon is from the CA021 Arbuckle TUD which is in 021AoA. The 021AoxA MUD states "As much as 30 to 50 percent of the soil material, by volume, is gravel and cobblestones." Rock fragments and textures will adjusted to reflect this amount stated. I am interpreting this concept as a skeletal taxadjunct.

There are just 2 polygons of AoxA with a total of 219 acres. They appear to be high energy stream terraces at the base of steep stream reaches that deposited coarse material from the foothills into the Stony Creek back valley.

Component ranges are from MUSum report and slopes were 0-1-3 % for report results Q10-Q50-Q90.

This map unit occurs at 1094 to 1165 feet elevation with 23 to 24 inches of precip determined by Q5 and Q95 from MUSum report.

There is no mention of minor comps in the MUD. The Hillgate and Artois minor components in the legacy dmu were replaced with Tehama, Cortina and Porterville based on adjacency and photo tone.

2y0f8: Arbuckle gravelly fine sandy loam, 0 to 2 percent slopes, MLRA 17

This is a map unit that updates 645Au. This tabular edit project updates mu and dmu of series in SSA that were updated in sdjr to standardize and update all the major components and component horizons of the series within the SSA. 645AvA was updated in sdjr as new mu 2t7r8 that used the CA645 TUD in 645AvA for component horizon.

CA645: Au; hgct; Tehama County, California - Arbuckle gravelly fine sandy loam, 0 to 3 percent slopes

The 645Au MUD states "This soil has a gravelly fine sandy loam surface soil but otherwise is similar to Arbuckle gravelly loam, 0 to 3 percent slopes" (645AvA). 645AvA is the TUD profile and has textures gl/gl/gl/gscl/vgl.

Awkwardly, the CA645 manuscript has lab data for Arbuckle "gravelly fine sandy loam", which is the 645Au phase concept, but there is no profile description of this lab profile because it is not the TUD profile.

The lab results for psa in the manuscript lab profile are gcosl/gcosl/gcosl/vgscl/xgcosl/xglcos/vgscl. These results contradict the MUD statement, and it is not unusual for lab data results to not have be incorporated into TUD profiles and concepts. In the past, when updating component horizons, I have typically incorporated the lab results when the lab profile is the same profile as the TUD.

The Storie Index and crop yield table in the CA645 manuscript rate AvA and Au the same, so they were not trying to flag Au as less productive. Panning around on imagery showed not noticeable droughtiness in Au vs. other Arbuckle mu.

I contacted Larry Branham, the DC in Red Bluff, to see if he had any experience in regard to Au being doughtier than other Arbuckle mu in CA645. He did not have any direct experience with Au, but felt if it was significantly coarser, he likely would have some awareness.

I am going to take the MUD statement as the concept for component horizon and not use the lab profile.

The MUSum slope results are 0-0-2% for Q10-Q50-Q90, so slopes will be changed to 0-2%.

This map unit occurs at 213 to 354 feet elevation with 24 to 27 inches of precip by Q5 and Q95.

2y0f9: Arbuckle gravelly loam, 0 to 7 percent slopes, MLRA 17

This is a map unit that updates 113AaB. This tabular edit project updates mu and dmu of series in SSA that were updated in sdjr to standardize and update all the major components and component horizons of the series within the SSA.

113AaA was updated in sdjr as new mu 2t7r8 that used the CA645 TUD in 645AvA for component horizon and combined 021AoA, 113AaA, 612178 and 645AvA. Combining these 4 mu into 1 mu seemed to align with the intent of sdjr. Because the individual mu were already within multiple LRU within CA645 and CA021 due to stream corridors in which they occur crossing LRU, and the minor extent of 612178, and the rational that LRU 7b and LRU 7g (113AaA) differences are somewhat arbitrary, they were combined despite varied LRU.

This initiated a complicated decision process in regard to deciding if I should use component horizon from 2t7r8 for this new dmu based on the prior decision of combining 113AaA with 3 other mu using the CA645 TUD for comp horizon, not the CA113 TUD.

Using the comp horizon from 2t7r8 would be using the CA645 TUD for component horizon for a mu that does not occur in CA645. I do not feel comfortable with that.

113AaB (2-5% slopes) did not get batched in the Arbuckle gravelly loam, 2 to 8 percent slopes project due to slope difference in names unfortunately.

021AoB was updated as a stand-alone mu (2w8cy) in the Arbuckle gravelly loam, 2 to 8 percent slopes project using the CA021 TUD in 021AoA for component horizon. The MuSum slopes for 021AoB were 0-3-19%, and due to line shift, I made the slopes 0-3-8%. So updated dmu for 021AoA and 021AoB have different profiles used for component horizons.

This initiated the thought of combining this new update dmu of 113AaB (0-1-7% by MUSum) with 2w8cy, and not getting hung up on the difference between 0-8% and 0-7% slopes.

Combining 113AaB with 2w8cy (021AoB) seemed like a possibility instead of making a new stand-alone mu for 113AaB. The CA113 TUD is in 113AaB, so it will be entered in pedon, and be a non-representative component pedon if I stick with the CA021 TUD for component horizon, and this dmu would not have a representative component pedon. I am more hesitant of merging these 2 mu due to LRU differences that are less varied than 2t7r8. This seems to contradict my decision for 2t7r8, but circumstances are somewhat different and the LRU occurrence is more straight forward.

Either of these 2 moves, as well as updating 113AaB as a stand-alone mu would cause the updated dmu for 113AaA and 113AaB to have different component horizons. Maybe in this era of MLRA map units, this is not as big a deal as it seems right now.

I am going to update 113AaB as a stand-alone mu, and use the CA113 TUD for component horizon that will have this profile, 1972CA113001, as a representative component horizon.

CA113: AaB; hdv4; Yolo County, California - Arbuckle gravelly loam, 2 to 5 percent slopes

The MUSum slope results are 0-1-7% for Q10-Q50-Q90, so slopes will be changed to 0-1-7%.

This map unit occurs at 236 to 525 feet elevation with 20 to 23 inches of precip by Q5 and Q95.

2y0fb: Arbuckle gravelly loam, 0 to 1 percent slopes, water table, MLRA 17

This is a map unit that updates 021Ap. This tabular edit project updates mu and dmu of series in SSA that were updated in sdjr to standardize and update all the major components and component horizons of the series within the SSA.

021AoA was updated in 2t7r8 which combined 021AoA, 113AaA, 612178 and 645AvA and the CA645 TUD was used for component horizon.

021AoB was updated in 2w8cy which combined 021AoB and 645AvB and the CA021 TUD was used for component horizon.

I will use the component horizon from 2w8cy and extract textures added from CA645 for this dmu component horizon because it is a closer representation of the CA021 concept. A water table will be added per MUD statement.

CA021: AvB; hd5y; Glenn County, California - Arbuckle gravelly loam, water table, 0 to 2 percent slopes

The 021Ap MUD states "The water table generally is within 3 feet of the surface during the ricegrowing season, but when the water is removed from the ricefields, the water table drop to a depth below 5 feet." Most of this mu looks to be linear low fan remnants fingering into the northern Colusa Basin, and a smaller extent occurs at the confluence of Hambright Creek and Stony Creek stream terraces. The majority of the extent that inter fingers with the northern Colusa Basin is mostly in or adjacent to rice fields. The smaller extent along Stony Creek looks to be irrigated pasture along the Stony Creek Irrigation Canal, which is concrete lined and existed during the survey and before Black Butte Reservoir was constructed. The MUD does not mention this setting, but the water table concept may have been intended for canal leaks and or excess irrigation along this corridor of irrigated pasture.

I have not encountered this kind of water table phase in regard to irrigation, but I will maintain it due to adjacency to rice production. I figure I will enter water tables from May through September.

MUSum slope results were 0-0-1% by Q10-Q50-Q90, so slopes will be changed.

This map unit occurs at 86 to 334 feet elevation with 23 to 24 inches of precip by MUSum results Q5 and Q95.

2y0fc: Arbuckle gravelly sandy loam, 0 percent slopes, MLRA 17

This is a map unit that updates 021As. This tabular edit project updates mu and dmu of series in SSA that were updated in sdjr to standardize and update all the major components and component horizons of the series within the SSA.

021AoA was updated in 2t7r8 which combined 021AoA, 113AaA, 612178 and 645AvA and the CA645 TUD was used for component horizon.

021AoB was updated in 2w8cy which combined 021AoB and 645AvB and the CA021 TUD was used for component horizon.

I will use the component horizon from 2w8cy and extract textures added from CA645 for this dmu component horizon because it is a closer representation of the CA021 concept. The 021As MUD states "This soil has a surface layer of gravelly sandy loam but otherwise is similar to Arbuckle gravelly loam, 0 to 2 percent slopes." The TUD profile will be used and the surface texture will be changed to gsl.

CA021: As; hd60; Glenn County, California - Arbuckle gravelly sandy loam, 0 to 2 percent slopes

MUSum slope results were 0-0-0% by Q10-Q50-Q90, so slopes will be changed.

This map unit occurs at 157 to 231 feet elevation with 22 to 24 inches of precip by MUSum results Q5 and Q95.

2y0fd: Arbuckle-Tehama complex, 0 to 8 percent slopes, MLRA 17

This is a map unit that updates 645Az. This tabular edit project updates mu and dmu of series in SSA that were updated in sdjr to standardize and update all the major components and component horizons of the series within the SSA. 645AvA was updated in sdjr as new mu 2t7r8 that used the CA645 TUD in 645AvA for component horizon.

CA645: Az; hgcz; Tehama County, California - Arbuckle-Tehama complex, 0 to 3 percent slopes

The 645Az MUD states "This complex consists of Arbuckle gravelly loam, 0 to 3 percent slopes, and Tehama loam, 0 to 3 percent slopes. Either soil may occupy from 20 to 80 percent of any one area."

The Arbuckle component horizon is from 2t7r8 which used the TUD from 645AvA.

The Tehama component horizon is from 2srj9 which used the CA645 TUD with the surface changed from silt loam to loam.

The MUSum slope results are 0-3-14% for Q10-Q50-Q90. After panning the polygons, it appears that in the foothills, some of the polygons were partly delineated on footslopes where these terraces are narrow, and delineating them at the original scale was difficult without overlapping on to the adjacent slopes. I think this is the case more than typical line shift. Throughout this mu extent there are risers and dissected channels that seem to have made the slope results higher than intended. I will adjust the slopes to 0-2-8% to balance the original concept with some of the reality. I will add a Sehorn minor component with slopes of 8 to 14% to try to reflect the footslopes in the foothills.

This map unit occurs at 331 to 892 feet elevation with 24 to 30 inches of precip by MUSum results Q5 and Q95.
